# Laravel Breeze AuthenticatedSessionController Overview

Based on the GitHub repository content, here's the complete `AuthenticatedSessionController` code structure:

## Full Controller Code

```php
<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers\Auth;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use App\Http\Requests\Auth\LoginRequest;
use Illuminate\Http\RedirectResponse;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Auth;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Route;
use Inertia\Inertia;
use Inertia\Response;

class AuthenticatedSessionController extends Controller
{
    public function create(): Response
    {
        return Inertia::render('Auth/Login', [
            'canResetPassword' => Route::has('password.request'),
            'status' => session('status'),
        ]);
    }

    public function store(LoginRequest $request): RedirectResponse
    {
        $request->authenticate();
        $request->session()->regenerate();
        return redirect()->intended(route('dashboard', absolute: false));
    }

    public function destroy(Request $request): RedirectResponse
    {
        Auth::guard('web')->logout();
        $request->session()->invalidate();
        $request->session()->regenerateToken();
        return redirect('/');
    }
}
```

## Key Session Handling Features

**Login Flow:** The `create()` method renders the login form via Inertia, while `store()` validates credentials, then "regenerates the session" to prevent fixation attacks.

**Logout Process:** The `destroy()` method performs three critical operations—guards logout, session invalidation, and CSRF token regeneration—ensuring complete session cleanup.

This implementation demonstrates Laravel Breeze's modern authentication approach using Inertia.js for frontend-backend communication with robust session management.

# Inertia.js Shared Data Implementation

## PHP Middleware Code

The documentation provides this example of the `HandleInertiaRequests` middleware:

```php
class HandleInertiaRequests extends Middleware
{
    public function share(Request $request)
    {
        return array_merge(parent::share($request), [
            // Synchronously...
            'appName' => config('app.name'),

            // Lazily...
            'auth.user' => fn () => $request->user()
                ? $request->user()->only('id', 'name', 'email')
                : null,
        ]);
    }
}
```

This middleware demonstrates sharing data "synchronously" (immediately available) and "lazily" (resolved only when needed).

## Accessing Shared Data in React

The documentation shows how to access this data in React components:

```jsx
import { usePage } from "@inertiajs/react";

export default function Layout({ children }) {
    const { auth } = usePage().props;

    return (
        <main>
            <header>You are logged in as: {auth.user.name}</header>
            <article>{children}</article>
        </main>
    );
}
```

## Important Note

The documentation mentions that "Shared data should be used sparingly as all shared data is included with every response." For one-time notifications, the guide recommends using flash data instead of shared data.

